$ PowerShell cmdLet get-culture

`get-culture` returns a → Microsoft/dot-net/namespaces-classes/System/Globalization/CultureInfo[`System.Globalization.CultureInfo`] object.

{ KeyboardLayoutId #KeyboardLayoutId

  The property `KeyboardLayoutId` (of the returned `CultureInfo`) is a number that identifes the current(?) culture's → hardware/keyboard.

  This number's eight-digit hexadecimal representation with leading zeroes is found in the registry
  under the registry key → Windows/registry/tree/HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE/System/CurrentControlSet/Control/Keyboard-Layouts[`HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Control\Keyboard Layouts`]. This
  → Windows/registry/tree-structure/key has the → Windows/registry/tree-structure/value `Layout Text` which provides a description for the keyboard layout id.

  The following → Windows/PowerShell script translates such a keyboard layout id to a text:
  gh|about-PowerShell|/cmdlets/culture/get/KeyboardLayoutId.ps1||

}

sa:
  → Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/noun/culture
